At last night's Board meeting, we presented a draft of "Closing the Distance," the district's plan for reopening schools. The plan also included some changes to the 2020-21 calendar, which the Board approved. The first day of virtual learning for students is Tuesday, September 8. The full list of changes is here: https://bit.ly/3hNblQb

City Schools will open the school year with virtual learning but continue to prepare a hybrid option. The draft reopening plan includes info about ways to safely reopen buildings later in the fall while providing families an option to continue virtual learning.

To give feedback on the plan, join us at the next Reopening Town Hall for families on Thursday, August 6, on Twitter, FB, or YouTube. https://www.baltimorecityschools.org/reopening

July 8 at 3:26 PM ·

Now offering home delivered grocery AND produce boxes.

Boxes are available for individuals and households in Baltimore City who meet all of the following criteria as a result of the COVID-19 emergency:
- Currently have no food at home or will run out before you can buy more
- Can't afford paid meal or grocery delivery
- Are experiencing financial, social or medical hardships due to COVID-19

To see if you qualify
Residents 59 and younger: call 2-1-1
Adults 60 and older: call 410-396-2273

#coronavirusbalt #keepyourdistance

Black fathers and their families from around Baltimore came together this past weekend for the Black Fathers Pledge Rally to pledge allegiance to black fatherhood, community, and each other. The rally was organized through a partnership among City Schools, Center for Urban Families, Stand Up for Baltimore, Black Fathers, Leaders of Tomorrow Youth Center, Maryland Mentor, and Black Fathers Foundation.

This powerful video, highlighting some of the speakers and families who attended, was produced by X-Media Productions LLC, a local company that was established by three recent City Schools alumni and former City Schools Student Media Team Reporters, Xavier Plater, Jacqueline Hammett, and Rommel Gainer.

post_text:
City Schools honors the 155th anniversary of Juneteenth.

Juneteenth commemorates the date, June 19, 1865, that the final enslaved people in Texas were notified by Union Soldiers that slavery had ended. This was more than two years after President Abraham Lincoln’s signing of the Emancipation Proclamation and months after the end of the Civil War.

To learn more about Juneteenth, resources, and ways to honor the day visit https://www.baltimorecityschools.org/juneteenth.

post_text:
Hundreds of students and their supporters showed up last week in a powerful way. Through a march and peaceful protest at the district office, they demanded that City Schools and the state take additional steps to provide an equitable education for black students.

Bryce Taylor, from the City Schools Student Media Team, caught up with student organizers, saw inspiring performances, and got a real understanding of what students truly want.

You can sign up to give live public comment between 4:30 and 5:30 p.m. today by emailing your name and phone number to kllawrence@bcps.k12.md.us. You will be called on during the forum to speak.

View the proposed budget and find out other ways to provide feedback: http://baltimorecityschools.org/budget

USTREAM.TV
City Schools TV
